# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: counter-strike-major-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They currently operate three franchise teams, which compete in the *Valorant* Champions Tour (VCT), *Apex Legends* Global Series (ALGS) (branded as Crazy Thieves), the Call of Duty League (CDL) (branded as Los Angeles Thieves).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves was founded in 2017 by Matthew "Nadeshot" Haag, a former OpTic Gaming *Call of Duty* team captain, (MLG) X Games gold medalist, and 2014 Esports Athlete of the year.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In November 2017, 100 Thieves received a multimillion-dollar investment from Cleveland Cavaliers and Quicken Loans owner Dan Gilbert allowing the company to expand into a full-fledged esports organization.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On October 23, 2018, 100 Thieves announced that they finished their Series A funding round co-led by Scooter Braun and Drake, who both became co-owners when they raised $25 million.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Included in this round was Sequoia Capital, Ludlow Ventures, Courtside Ventures, WndrCo, Marc Benioff, Drew Houston, Green Bay Ventures, Tao Capital and Advancit Capital.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Their Series B funding round on July 16, 2019, was led by Artist Capital Management which raised $35 million.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Included in this round is Aglae Ventures, Groupe Arnault (controlling shareholder of Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessy).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In March 2021, 100 Thieves signed a sponsorship deal with Truly Seltzer and Twisted Tea.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They acquired gaming peripheral company Higround in October 2021, marking their first acquisition.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On December 2, 2021, 100 Thieves announced their Series C funding round, which raised $60 million.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In May 2022, 100 Thieves announced its intentions to publish a video game.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] It hired former Telltale Games CEO Pete Hawley as its Chief Product Officer to set up a studio.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In July, more than 10 members of 100 Thieves' content team were laid off.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Nadeshot launched his own energy drink, called Juvee, on October 4.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In January 2023, around 30 employees were laid off, including several lead staff members.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] That November, 100 Thieves announced it was laying off 20% of its workforce, affecting employees at its game studio and energy drink brand.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] These business units would also be spun off as separate companies in order to focus on esports and apparel.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On May 6, 2024, the Esports World Cup Foundation, funded by the Saudi Arabia Public Investment Fund and organizers of the Esports World Cup tournament series, announced the 30 organizations (known in the ESWC as Clubs) who would make up the Club Support Program, with 100 Thieves being one of them.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] This program gives teams a one-time six-figure stipend if an organization is willing to enter new esports as well as additional funding each year if they drive viewership and fan engagement to the Esports World Cup.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In December 2024, Nadeshot revealed that he would be taking a step back from 100 Thieves to pursue full-time content creation.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In September 2025, Nadeshot confirmed that he is no longer the CEO of 100 Thieves, but remains involved with the organization in other roles.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In February 2019, 100 Thieves announced their entrance in the Apex Legends competitive scene, signing Connor "Gigz" White, Justin "Teenage" Phipps, and Isiah "Lifted" Slowik as their first roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In August 2019, 100 Thieves announced Justin "JP2" Pate as their fourth roster member.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the same month, 100 Thieves announced their exit from the Apex Legends scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In October 2021, 100 Thieves returned to Apex Legends, signing the roster of Brendan "Onmuu" Pode, Alex "scuwry" Scala, and Nicholas "Vein" Hobbs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In February 2022, the team released Vein and signed Alan "Vaxlon" Gonzalez, with Tyler "Sickks" Clark joining later on as their new head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team placed 3rd in the 2022 Apex Legends Global Series World Championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In September 2023, 100 Thieves released their entire roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In November 2024, 100 Thieves announced the roster of Tyler "Dezignful" Gardner, Noyan "Genburten" Ozkose, and 100 Thieves content creator Timothy "iiTzTimmy" An, with Deston "Bronzey" Nguyen as the head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After being eliminated in the group stage of the 2024 Apex Legends Global Series World Championship, Dezignful announced that he would be exploring his options for next season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In March 2025, 100 Thieves announced the departures of Dezingful and iiTzTimmy and announced the signings of Josue "Phony" Ruiz and Evan "Verhulst" Verhulst to join Genburten for the 2025 season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In September 2025, Bronzey stepped down as head coach and was replaced by Balvarine.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In January 2026, 100 Thieves announced a collaboration with the Japanese esports organization Crazy Raccoon, branding the team as the "Crazy Thieves" for the Year 5 Championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The following month, Balvarine would step down as the team's head coach and was replaced by Daniel "Nihil" Freudenthal.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team started the season off signing the team of Kenneth "Kenny" Williams, Maurice "Fero" Henriquez, Sam "Octane" Larew, Austin "SlasheR" Liddicoat, and Ian "Enable" Wyatt.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They placed 9th–12th at CWL Las Vegas 2019, qualifying for the Pro League Qualifiers and for the Pro League.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After this, they had to re-evaluate the roster, and acquired Preston "Priestahh" Greiner and head coach James "Crowder" Crowder on loans from FaZe Clan, with Fero getting benched.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At CWL Fort Worth 2019, the team finished 4th losing to Team Reciprocity, citing medical issues with player Priestahh and being replaced by Fero.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At CWL London 2019, the team won the organization's first trophy.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At CWL Anaheim 2019, the team won the organization's second trophy.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After the Pro League, 100 Thieves finished second in Division B, qualifying for Pro League playoffs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At the Pro League Playoffs, the team placed 5th–6th, losing to Gen.G esports.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the 2019 Call of Duty World Championship, 100 Thieves finished second, with a loss to eUnited.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After initially announcing their intention to not join the Call of Duty League in 2019, 100 Thieves announced in November 2020 that they would enter the league as the "Los Angeles Thieves" after acquiring OpTic Gaming's slot.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the 2022 season, the Los Angeles Thieves defeated the Atlanta FaZe to the win the 2022 Call of Duty League World Championship, bringing the organization their first ever world championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 10, 2025, 100 Thieves announced that their entry into the Counter-Strike 2 competitive scene, marking their return to *Counter-Strike* esports for the first time since October 2020.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The organization also announced the online casino Roobet as the team's title sponsor and the team will play under the name "100 Thieves Roobet".
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 12, the team made their first signings with the hirings of Graham "messioso" Pitt as Head of CS Operations and Sean "sgares" Gares as Head of FPS.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The latter had previously been head coach for their Valorant team and will be working with both the Counter-Strike 2 and Valorant divisions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 13, 100 Thieves announced their first player in multi-time HLTV MVP Håvard "rain" Nygaard.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On December 19, 100 Thieves announced Lukas "gla1ve" Rossander as their head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On January 5, 2026, 100 Thieves announced the signings of André "Ag1l" Gil, Alex "poiii" Sundgren, and William "sirah" Kjærsgaard.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The following day, the team was finalized with the signing Nicolai "dev1ce" Reedtz.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves parted ways with Tensa as their head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In June 2025, Luis "iRemiix" Figueroa and Kamryn "Malenia" Mistry were hired as the team's new coaches with Malenia also being a substitute, while Billion would leave the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] A month later, Jacob "Nuk" Allen was signed to the roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 17, 100 Thieves announced that they would be leaving the Marvel Rivals competitive scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On February 10, 2026, 100 Thieves announced that they have re-joined the Marvel Rivals scene as part of the Marvel Rivals Partner Program, re-signing Delenna, Malenia, TTK, Vinnie with IRemiix as the head coach to join the new additions of Bryce “Self” Pettit and Pol “Wyni” Carracedo.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On February 14, 2026, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Rainbow Six Siege competitive scene as part of the R6 Partner Program.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On March 9, 100 Thieves announced their inaugural roster of Adam "Atom" Gutierrez, Arthur "GMZ" Oliveria, Roberto "Panbazou" Feliciano, Zachary "SpiriTz" Dionne, and Evan "Yoggah" Nelson with the coaching staff of Luiz "Kizi" Sirico and Kaique "Kpan" Pantojo.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On June 4, 2020, 100 Thieves Esports announced their entrance into the Valorant competitive scene through the signing of Spencer "Hiko" Martin.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Within three weeks of signing Hiko, the team was finalized.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also signed Hector "FrosT" Rosario as their head coach but he was announced until months later.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The original team consisted of in-game leader Keane "Valliate" Alonso, Diondre "YaBoiDre" Bond, Zachary "Venerated" Roach, and Alfred "Pride" Choi.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] This team, however, did not last long; on August 14, 2020, the entire team, apart from Hiko, was released.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Shortly thereafter, the team went on to sign Counter-Strike: Global Offensive veterans Nick "nitr0" Cannella and in-game leader Joshua "steel" Nissan.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 2 months later, the team was once again finalized after signing Peter "Asuna" Mazuryk and Quan "dicey" Tran from Immortals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team went on to win the very first Valorant First Strike tournament, defeating TSM in the grand finals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On January 26, 2021, the team brought in Jonathan "silenx" Huntington as a substitute in place of nitr0, due to nitr0's wife going into labor.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Nitr0 returned to the team shortly after.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On February 28, 2021, the team benched dicey in favor of another veteran CS:GO player, Ethan "Ethan" Arnold.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After the Masters 3 tourney, the team decided to call up their substitute Aaron "b0i" Thao to the starting roster, moved steel to the bench, and appointed nitr0 as full-time in-game leader.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also added Johann "seven" Hernandez as a substitute.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Their 2021 season ended after falling to Cloud9 in the NA Last Chance Qualifier for Valorant Champions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 23, dicey and b0i were dropped from the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Soon after, both steel and nitr0 departed the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They started 2022 with the signing of in-game leader Adam "ec1s" Eccles and Hunter "BabyJ" Schline and promoting analyst Jovanni "Jovi" Vera to head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Shockingly, after two losses in the 2022 NA VCT Challengers Stage 1 group stage, ec1s and BabyJ were released; the team then acquired Sean "bang" Bezerra from TSM and Noah "jcStani" Smith from Kansas City Pioneers on loans and Ethan was appointed as in-game leader.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After being eliminated in the 2022 NA VCT Challengers group stage, the team parted ways with Jovi and hired Sean "sgares" Gares as head coach with Michael "Mikes" Hockom joining him as an assistant, and hiring Daniel "ddk" Kapadia as general manager.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On March 27, jcStani announced his free agency after his loan period ended with the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On April 12, Hiko announced his retirement from competitive Valorant but remained with the organization as a content creator.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] A couple days later, bang was fully bought out and the team then signed Derrek "Derrek" Ha, in-game leader Brenden "stellar" McGrath, and William "Will" Cheng, while Ethan was moved to the bench and later released.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team was able to qualify for 2022 Valorant Champions after beating The Guard in the grand finals of the NA Last Chance Qualifier.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team was then placed Group D alongside DRX, FURIA Esports, and Fnatic.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished the tournament 9-12th.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Following the end of the regular 2022 season, 100 Thieves released Will and signed XSET star player Matthew "Cryo" Panganiban, and Mikes was promoted to head coach, following Sgares's departure.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves ended the year by winning the Red Bull Home Ground tournament #3 in Manchester with a 3–0 win over Cloud9 in December 2022.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In September 2022, 100 Thieves was selected as one of the thirty teams to be part of Riot Games' partnership program for the 2023 season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] During the season, they failed to qualify to Americas League playoffs and were also eliminated in their first match in the Americas Last Chance Qualifier.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On September 12, 2023, 100 Thieves announced the release of Derrek and stellar.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On September 25, 2023, 100 Thieves signed Tony "Zikz" Gray as head coach, who had previously been head coach for their League of Legends team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Mikes was moved back to assistant coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 1, 2023, 100 Thieves announced Daniel "eeiu" Vucenovic to the starting roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves competed in the main event of Red Bull Home Ground #4 in Tokyo with Nicholas "NaturE" Garrison as a stand-in and interim in-game leader, and placed fifth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On January 8, 2024, 100 Thieves rounded out their roster with in-game leader, Kelden "Boostio" Pupello.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Boostio, along with Zikz, previously won the 2023 Valorant Champions with Evil Geniuses.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The season started off poorly with 100 Thieves losing all their games in the Kickoff tournament and being eliminated.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In Americas Stage 1, they placed second in their group and qualified for the playoffs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] With a clean sweep of their playoff games including a 3–0 win over G2 Esports in the grand final, they became Stage 1 champions and qualified to Masters Shanghai as the first seed from Americas, earning a bye to the playoffs and 9 circuit points for the 2024 Valorant Champions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At Shanghai, they placed 4th after beating FUT and Paper Rex but losing to both eventual finalists Gen.G and Team Heretics.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] With a 2–3 record in Americas Stage 2, the team made it into playoffs but placed 4th, ending their year one win away from qualifying to Champions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On October 3, it was announced that Bang would be leaving after two and a half years with the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On October 8, Alexander "Zander" Dituri was announced as the new fifth member of the roster with Yury "frenya" Elkin and Rudi "rudi" Mcken joining the coaching staff later on.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After a subpar start to the year, being eliminated immediately from 2025 Kickoff, and not making it to Masters Toronto either, 100 Thieves placed second in the 2025 Esports World Cup qualifier and became one of four Americas teams to qualify for Riyadh.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They lost both matches played at EWC and were eliminated in last place.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On July 19, Boostio was benched and Drew "Kess" Lee was added to the roster, while Zander would take over in-game leading duties.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In Stage 2, 100 Thieves finished with a 3–2 record in group stage, but were eliminated by Cloud9 in the Stage 2 playoffs and failed to qualify for Champions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After being eliminated, 100 Thieves allowed all members of the roster and coaching staff to explore their options of the 2026 season as restricted free agents.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] During the offseason, majority of the roster and all of the coaching staff left, while Asuna and Cryo stayed.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 6, the team announced the signings of TSM trio Timothée "Timotino" Dupont, in-game leader Jordan "vora" Pulwer, and 2021 Valorant Champion Laurynas "Nbs" Kisielius as their new head coach with Erik "d00mbr0s" Sandgren as an assistant.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The following day, the team finalized their roster for the 2026 season by re-signing Bang, who departed the team the offseason prior.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 12, the team announced that Sgares would be returning to the team as the Head of FPS, primarily working with the Valorant and Counter-Strike 2 divisions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On August 19, C4Lypso stepped down as head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On September 25, Harry "zelo" Davies was hired as the team's new head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On February 4, 2026, 100 Thieves released their entire roster (barring Lidyuh) and coaching staff, signing Misu, scaryshark32, terror, and zoriental with Tanishq "Tanizhq" Sabharwal as head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In April 2026, 100 Thieves released their entire roster and left the *Valorant Game Changer* scene.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On June 1, 2026, 100 Thieves announced a collaboration with Your Favorite Player (YFP) to form a new Valorant team to compete in the *Valorant Challengers* scene branded as "Your Favorite Thieves" or "YFT".
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They inherited YFP's team that included David “atlas” Griffiths, Jaiden “devy” Mantz, Bradley “Muddy” Saephan, Ali “stallion” Kadhim, and Damion “XXiF” Cook.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In November 2020, 100 Thieves entered the Call of Duty: Warzone competitive scene announcing Thomas "Tommey" Trewren and Rhys "Rated Price" as their first players.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In October 2022, Tommey left the team, with Rated also leaving a month later.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In April 2025, 100 Thieves returned to the scene for the 2025 Esports World Cup, announcing the roster of Rasim "Blazt" Ogresevic, Gabe "GabeKunn" Kunn, Logan "Skullface" Greifelt, and Ethan "Ebatez" Bates as head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In October 2025, t100 Thieves exited the scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In April 2018, 100 Thieves was announced as member of the Clash Royale League.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the following months, 100 Thieves announced the roster of Eduadro "Eddie" Rojas-Torras, Jacob "Frost" Horsch, James "Pt105" Keresey, and Hoan "PureZuhn" Le, with Davis "Gilgamesh" Huang as head coach and William "Woody" Hix as the team's general manager.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In December 2018, 100 Thieves announced their departure from competitive Clash Royale.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In December 2017, 100 Thieves announced that they signed the former roster of Immortals which included players Bruno "BIT" Lima, Lincoln "fnx" Lau, Henrique "HEN1" Teles, Vito "kNgV-" Giuseppe, and Lucas "LUCAS1" Teles with Rodolfo "bLecker" Blecker as head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] However, the organization had issues with visas, resulting in the team being disbanded.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In late October 2019, 100 Thieves announced the signing of the former Renegades roster which included Aaron "AZR" Ward, Sean "Gratisfaction" Kaiwai, Joakim "jkaem" Myrbostad, Justin "jks" Savage, and Jay "Liazz" Tregillgas with Aleksandar "kassad" Trifunović as head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At IEM Beijing 2019, the team placed second in the tournament, losing to Astralis.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team placed 7th–8th at the ESL Season 10 Pro League Finals, losing to Fnatic.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In April 2020, head coach Kassad was mutually let go from the team and Chet "Chet" Singh was hired as the new head coach a month later.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On October 12, 2020, 100 Thieves announced their departure from the competitive CS:GO scene, citing complications with travel, a focus on European events, and COVID-19 as the main reasons behind the move.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In July 2018, 100 Thieves announced their entrance into the Fortnite: Battle Royale competitive scene, announcing the signings of Kenith, Archie "Parallax" Sharder, and Alex "Risker" Biamonte, with SirDimetrious joining a month later.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At the beginning of 2019, Risker and Parallax were released and the team signed Maurilio "Blind" Gramajo, Davis "Ceice" McClellan, Hayden "Elevate" Krueger, Brandon "Klass" Weaver, and Gabriel "Kyuzi" Harlos.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At the end of 2019, Blind, Kenith, and SirDimetrious were released, with the team signing Diego "Arkhram" Lima, Brendan "Falconer" Facloner, and Brett "grandmateets" Squires.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] At the Fortnite World Cup, Ceice and Elevate placed 3rd in the duos competition, while Arkhram and Falconer placed 5th.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In 2020, the team signed Martin "MrSavage" Andersen and Brodie "rehx" Franks, with Grandmateets, Klass, and Kyzui leaving the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In February 2021, Ceice and Elevate left the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The next year, 100 Thieves exited the Fortnite: Battle Royale competitive scene, releasing the remaining roster members.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] On November 20, 2017, 100 Thieves was accepted as a franchise organization for the 2018 NA LCS season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team signed Neil "pr0lly" Hammad as its head coach and Kim "Ssumday" Chan-ho, William "Meteos" Hartman, Ryu "Ryu" Sang-wook, Cody Sun, and Zaqueri "Aphromoo" Black for its starting roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team placed first in the spring split regular season with a 12–6 record, securing a bye into the semifinals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Additionally, Aphromoo was voted as MVP of the spring split.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The first team they faced in the playoffs was Clutch Gaming, and 100 Thieves won 3–2, moving on to the finals, where they were swept 0–3 by Team Liquid in the finals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves' second-place finish qualified them for Rift Rivals 2018, an international tournament between the top three spring teams from Europe and North America.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team elected to use substitute player Đỗ "Levi" Duy Khánh in place of Meteos for the tournament.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Team Liquid, 100 Thieves, and Echo Fox competed against Europe's Fnatic, G2 Esports, and Splyce, going a combined 4–5 in the double round-robin group stage with 100 Thieves with a 1–2 record after a single win against Splyce.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the best-of-five "relay race" finals, the team lost their game against Fnatic, contributing to North America's combined 1–3 loss to Europe.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Before the summer split, 100 Thieves traded Meteos to Flyquest, in exchange for their jungler, Andy "AnDa" Hoang.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Following this roster move, the team placed third in the regular season with a 10–8 record.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team won their first match 3–0 over FlyQuest, before losing 1–3 to Team Liquid in the semi-finals, then losing 2–3 in the third place match to Team SoloMid.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team's performance across both splits allowed them to qualify for the 2018 League of Legends World Championship in South Korea as North America's second seed.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team was drawn to Group D with Europe's Fnatic, China's Invictus Gaming, and Hong Kong's G-Rex.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Shortly after qualifying for the world championship, they replaced Cody Sun with substitute player Richard "Rikara" Oh.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves finished third in their group with a 2–4 record, and 12th overall, not qualifying for the knockout stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In 2019, the team extended top laner Ssumday's contract, while Ryu moved to an assistant position.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Cody Sun and Rikara opted to leave the team, and they were replaced by Choi "huhi" Jae-hyun and Bae "Bang" Jan-sik.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Partway through the spring split, Huhi was benched in favor for Max "Soligo" Soong, but despite attempts at change, the team finished the spring split in dead last, with a 4–14 record, and elected to make additional roster changes for summer.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Huhi left the team, and Maurice "Amazing" Stückenschneider joined to replace AnDa, who was moved to the academy roster along with Ryu.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] A month into the split, the team replaced Soligo with Ryu from the academy roster, and also swapped Ssumday with Aaron "FakeGod" Lee, as LCS rules required at least 3 North American residents on the starting roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished the summer split in eighth place and did not qualify for the post–season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves began the 2020 season with the announcement that Chris "PapaSmithy" Smith would be joining the team as the new general manager.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Tony "Zikz" Gray was the next addition to the roster, replacing pr0lly as head coach, and both Meteos and Cody Sun rejoined the team for the second time, alongside new additions William "Stunt" Chen and Tommy "Ryoma" Le.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Ryu, Amazing, Bang and Aphromoo all left the team, with FakeGod rejoining Academy and Ssumday rejoining the main roster.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In spring, the team finished third in the regular season with a 10–8 record, and qualified for post–season for the first time since 2018.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] However once in the playoffs, they were swept 0–3 by Cloud9, and then lost 2–3 to Team SoloMid in the losers' bracket.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After an 1–5 start in the summer split, the team parted ways with players Meteos and Stunt, and called up academy players Juan "Contractz" Garcia and Philippe "Poome" Lavoie-Giguere to replace them.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished in seventh at the end of the summer split with a 7–11 record, and were seeded into the loser's bracket of the playoffs, where they would be swept 0–3 by Evil Geniuses to finish their 2020 season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The 2021 season started with the team signing Can "Closer" Çelik, Victor "FBI" Huang, Tanner "Damonte" Damonte, and a returning Huhi from Golden Guardians.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Ry0ma (renamed from Ryoma) and Poome were moved to the academy roster, while Cody Sun and Contractz both left the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also added Aleš "Freeze" Kněžínek and Ham "Lustboy" Jang-sik to the coaching staff.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The season started off with the preseason Lock−In tournament, and the team starting strong, placing first in their group, before sweeping Immortals 2–0 in the first round of the knock−out stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the semifinals they faced Cloud9, and despite winning the first two games, were reverse swept to lose 2–3 in the series, and finish 3rd/4th in the tournament.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In week 5 of the spring split, the team decided to bring back Ry0ma as their starter and sent Damonte to academy.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They finished the spring split in third place, and in the Mid-Season Showdown, were swept 0–3 by Cloud9, before picking up a 3–0 win of their own against Dignitas in the losers bracket.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team faced Team SoloMid next, and fell 1–3, and were eliminated from playoffs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After a fourth-place finish in the spring split, the team parted ways with head coach Zikz and hired Bok "Reapered" Han-gyu as his replacement.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Prior to the start of the summer split, 100 Thieves signed Felix "Abbedagge" Braun from the LEC, and Ry0ma was subsequently sent back to academy, while Damonte was dropped by the organization.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The revamped roster would go on to finish second in the regular season, with a record of 29–16.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team won their first playoff match 3–2 against Evil Geniuses, before falling 2–3 to Team Liquid.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the losers' bracket, 100 Thieves defeated Cloud9 3–1 to set up a finals rematch against Team Liquid.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] This time around, 100 Thieves defeated Team Liquid in a 3–0 sweep, to win the 2021 LCS Championship and qualify for the 2021 League of Legends World Championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team's performance secured them a bye into Group B alongside China's Edward Gaming, Korea's T1, and Japan's DetonatioN FocusMe.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished third in their group, with a 3–3 record, and were eliminated from the tournament, placing 9th–12th overall and ending their season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In 2022, the team announced all five players would be returning, with academy top laner Milan "Tenacity" Oleksij as a sixth man.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Alfonso "Mithy" Rodriguez also joined the coaching staff in the off−season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Once again, 100 Thieves were atop their group in the Lock−In tournament, however they were upset 0–2 by Dignitas in the quarterfinals of the Knock−Out stage, and eliminated early.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Through the first round robin of the spring split, 100 Thieves accumulated a 5–4 record, putting them in a three-way tie for third place.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] 100 Thieves ultimately ended the spring split with a record of 12–6, securing themselves third place.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In the first round of Playoffs, they swept Cloud 9 3–0 to advance to the winner bracket finals, where they came back from a 0–2 deficit to reverse sweep Team Liquid and advance to Grand Finals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] There, they lost 0–3 to Evil Geniuses, denying 100 Thieves back to back championships.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Following a group stage exit at the 2022 World Championship, General manager PapaSmithy and coaches Repeared, Mithy, and Freeze parted ways with the team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] For the 2023 season, 100 Thieves released the entire roster except Closer, signing veterans Yiliang "Doublelift" Peng and Søren "Bjergsen" Bjerg and promoting Alan "Busio" Cwalina from the academy, and Tenacity to full-time top laner.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also hired Christopher "Kaas" Oudheusden as their new head coach with Erlend "Nukeduck" Holm joining as an assistant and promoting Joseph "JungleJuice" Jang as general manager.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After a 5–8 start to the Spring Split, Kaas and 100 Thieves parted ways and Nukeduck was promoted to interim head coach with Danny "Dan Dan" Comte joining as an assistant from the challengers team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Following a quick exit in Spring playoffs, Bjergsen announced his retirement.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After Bjergsen's retirement, the team announced their new head coach in Jang "Cain" Nu-ri and the signing of Lim "Quid" Hyeon-seung as their new mid laner.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also brought back Ssumday as Tenacity decided to move to content creation.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished with a 7–11 record and placed 7th-8th in the summer split championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] For the 2024 season, the team parted ways with the whole roster and coaching staff except for Quid, signing Rayan "Sniper" Shoura, Kim "River" Dong-woo, Brandon "Meech" Choi, and Bill "Eyla" Nguyen.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team also announced Greyson "Goldenglue" Gilmer as their new head coach.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished 5th-8th in the Spring playoffs with a 10–4 record in the regular season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] During the Summer split, Meech was benched and the team signed Frank "Tomo" Lam.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The team finished the regular season with a 3–4 record and finished 3rd in the Summer playoffs and qualified for the 2024 World Championship play-in, where they would be eliminated by PSG Talon.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In November 2024, Tomo was released and FBI was re-signed as the new starting bot laner.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] They finished the regular season of Split 1 in first place, but finished as runner-ups in the playoffs, losing to Team Liquid 0–3 in the grand finals In Split 2, they finished 3rd in the regular season standings and placed top 6 in the playoffs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In July 2025, 100 Thieves announced that they would be exiting the LTA and League of Legends competitive scene after the 2025 season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In August 2025, Nishp "Dhokla" Doshi was added to the roster as a sixth man.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In October 2025, T1 defeated 100 Thieves at the 2025 Worlds tournament, resulting in their withdrawal from *League of Legends*.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Street Fighter competitive scene with signing of Sean "Shine" Simpson.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] After placing 25th-36th in the 2025 Esports World Cup, Shine was quietly released and 100 Thieves exited the Street Fighter competitive scene.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Teamfight Tactics competitive scene with the roster of Joseph "Dishsoap" Goldsmith, Yoo "Kiyoon" Ki-yoon, Rereplay, and Spencer "Spencer" Zhou.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] In December 2025, the roster was released and 100 Thieves exited the scene.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The 100 Thieves Compound is a 15,000 square foot esports, entertainment, and apparel hub, located in Culver City, California.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] It has four sports training rooms: the Rocket Mortgage League of Legends training room, the AT&T Valorant training room, the Totino's Fortnite training room, and the League of Legends Academy training room.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] It also has a content studio, which is worth around half a million dollars.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Other areas include the Cash App Lounge, the Totino's basketball court, many business operation areas and four streaming pods.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] Chairs, catering, and PCs are provided by Secretlab, Chipotle and NZXT respectively.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] It was formerly known as the 100 Thieves Cash App Compound.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/100-thieves] The compound served as an LA County vote center for the 2020 United States presidential election.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2007-in-esports] In Major League Gaming, Team Final Boss beat Team Carbon to win the MLG Las Vegas 2007 National Championship.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2007-in-esports] In the Championship Gaming Series their series began in 2007, with the 2007 Championship Gaming Series season.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2007-in-esports] At the time it was the most expensive esports tournament of all time.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2013-in-esports] This article documents the year 2013 in esports.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2014-in-esports] List of events in 2014 in esports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2016-in-esports] List of events in 2016 in eSports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The **2017 Visa Vegas eRace** was an eSports Formula E race held on January 7, 2017, at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino in Las Vegas, Nevada, as part of the Sports Business Innovation Summit at the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] This race, unlike others, did not count towards the 2016-17 season and was not held on a real track.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Ten sim racers—competitors who typically enter simulation racing video games—raced against regular series drivers on a simulated course for a $1 million total prize fund, a record in eSports racing history.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The race consisted of two races: a 14-lap qualifying race for the slowest 20 qualifiers to determine positions 11 to 20 for the 20-lap main race; and a 20-lap main race.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] An earlier qualifying session, divided into five groups of six cars, determined the first ten starting positions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis, a Dragon sim driver, led every session and won the event from pole position.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] António Félix da Costa, a professional driver, won the earlier qualifying race.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis led for the majority of the race until the mandatory virtual pit stops to change into a second car, when Mahindra's Olli Pahkala took over.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala finished first on the road after leading the final five laps, but he was penalised 12 seconds after it was discovered that a software bug allowed him to use FanBoost for longer than allowed.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Felix Rosenqvist, the highest-placed professional driver for Mahindra, took second, while Pakhala's penalty dropped him to third.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace received mixed reviews in the media.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Those who criticised the race criticised its organisation because multiple technical issues caused a half-hour delay in the main event, and one driver was forced to withdraw from both races due to simulator issues.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Positive reviewers expressed their belief that the event's consequences could lead to a professional eSports racing series and aid in the resolution of accessibility issues, as well as for others to use it as an alternative career to traditional motor racing.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Following the eRace, some sim racers were adopted into the teams to which they were assigned, assisting their real-life development through car testing and advice.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Luis Pachon, the founder of the Madrid-based start-up company Cloud Sport, proposed the idea for an eRace in Las Vegas to Formula E (FE) CEO Alejandro Agag, who quickly understood Pachon's intention and began work soon after.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] *iRacing* was reportedly an early contender for an association with FE, but the costs of laser scanning the track, and the lack of a wider benefit of putting in the effort of constructing the circuit, meant it was not cost effective.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Agag revealed the eRace plans to *Reuters* in June 2016, and announced that it would take place during the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show (CES).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] FE had previously held eRaces at all championship rounds, in which spectators competed against professional racing drivers in the eVillage of the hosting race track.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace was officially confirmed at the 2016 London ePrix the following month.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] It was held on January 7, 2017, as part of CES' Sport Business Innovation Summit at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino, but it did not count towards the 2016–17 championship and no points were awarded.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] For this event, FE partnered with ELEAGUE and featured commentary from Jack Nicholls and Dario Franchitti.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace featured 20 FE competitors from the regular season grid and ten sim racing drivers who qualified for the event by competing in the Road to Vegas Challenge, a four-race elimination contest held between October 16 and December 4, 2016.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Former Formula Ford 1600 driver Graham Carroll and iRacing world champion Greger Huttu qualified first and second for the eRace.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the ten sim drivers was assigned to one of the ten genuine FE teams at random.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] For realism, each participant wore a flame-proof race suit and drove identical virtual cars, with the only difference being team liveries and personal numbers for identification.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pit stops to virtually switch to a second car were mandatory.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The race was regulated by FE's sporting director, and motorsport's world governing body, the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The total prize fund was $1 million (the largest in eSports racing history), and was broadcast on the live streaming platform Twitch.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport designed the 3.14-mile (5.05 km) long anti-clockwise track, which was publicly unveiled on January 6.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers started on South Las Vegas Boulevard, passing hotels and casino resorts such as the Luxor and the MGM Grand.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport supplied and regulated the Playseat simulation equipment which operated on the racing video game *rFactor 2.* Thrustmaster TS-PC steering wheels and T3PA pedals were fitted to the equipment.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The stewards sealed and approved all computers to ensure parity.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] External ports were blocked to prevent anyone from connecting personal components.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers were unable to feel G-forces during the race, so Cloud Sport programmed the vehicles to respond to the inertia created by sudden acceleration.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] This created a realistic driving experience, as vehicles tilted onto three wheels during sharp cornering, and the cars' performance deteriorated when they were damaged.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The Vegas eRace was heavily promoted beforehand.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] If all you do is race on simulators at home, then maybe they are pretty good!." According to Mahindra's Felix Rosenqvist, the sim racers would have an advantage due to their experience, but it would not be as significant after learning the circuit.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Four practice sessions were held before the qualification race on January 7.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The first session, held on January 6, lasted half an hour and was attended by sim drivers, followed by an identically timed session for professional racing drivers fifteen minutes later.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] On the morning of January 7, the final two sessions for sim and professional drivers each lasted fifteen minutes.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis set the fastest time for Dragon in the combined opening practice session, 1 minute, 28.456 seconds, half a second faster than anyone else.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] His closest rival was professional driver Rosenqvist, who finished second, ahead of third-placed Graham Carroll and Virgin's José María López in fourth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet was fifth, ahead of sixth-placed António Félix da Costa.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Sam Bird, Enzo Bonito, Olli Pahkala and Frijns rounded out the top ten fastest drivers in the session.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis again led the combined time sheets in the second practice session, this time with a lap of 1 minute, 28.142 seconds, more than half a second faster than second-placed Frijns; Rosenqvist was third, Félix da Costa was fourth, Petar Brljak was fifth, and Graham Carroll was sixth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was seventh, Bonito eighth, David Greco ninth and López tenth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Saturday afternoon's 50 minute qualifying session was divided into five groups of six cars.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The groups were determined by a lottery system and were permitted six minutes of on-track activity.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The fastest five overall competitors in all five groups participated in a "Super Pole" session with one driver on the track at any time going out in reverse order from fifth to first.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the five drivers was limited to one timed lap and the starting order was determined by their' fastest times.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] (Super Pole from first to fifth, and group qualifying from sixth to tenth).
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis continued to top every session throughout the eRace meeting and achieved pole position with a lap of 1 minute, 28.631 seconds.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] He received a $25,000 automatic award for his achievement.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Rosenqvist, whose fastest lap was two-tenths of a second slower, joined Huis on the front row.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Sim racers rounded out the top ten, with Aleksi Uusi-Jaakkola third and Graham Carroll fourth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Greco finished fifth out of five super pole competitors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Sixth to tenth place went to Pahkala, Patrik Holzmann, Huttu, Bonito, and Alkesi Elomaa.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Lucas di Grassi, Ma Qinghua, Bird, Maro Engel, Jean-Éric Vergne, Jérôme d'Ambrosio, Daniel Abt, Sébastien Buemi, Mitch Evans, Stéphane Sarrazin, Loïc Duval, Nico Prost, Oliver Turvey, Adam Carroll, Petar Brjlak (who crashed during his run) and Nick Heidfeld completed the starting order.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] From 15:25 Pacific Standard Time (PST) (UTC+08:00), the slowest 20 drivers from group qualifying competed in a 14-lap qualifying race to determine positions 11 to 20 on the grid.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] D'Ambrosio failed to start due to technical problems with his racing pod.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] In a race marred by multiple crashes that resulted in several cars losing bodywork parts, López led from the start until Félix da Costa closed in on him and overtook him on the outside at turn five.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Félix da Costa led the rest of the race to finish first and start 11th in the main race.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] López finished second and Frijns came third.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Outside the top three, Piquet secured fourth and was followed closely behind by Evans and Bird in fifth and sixth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Defending series champion Buemi took seventh ahead of di Grassi in eighth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The final two qualifiers were Di Grassi's teammate Abt and Duval in ninth and tenth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The "Fan Boost" feature, which provided an additional 100 kW (130 hp) of power for six seconds in the driver's second car, was a unique feature of FE.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] A fan vote determined which three drivers were allowed to use the boost.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala, López, and Greco were given the extra power for the Vegas eRace.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The race was due to begin at 16:05 PST, but due to multiple technical issues, it was delayed for half an hour and reduced from 28 to 20 laps.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Di Grassi failed to start due to a simulator control issue.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The exact number of viewers was not disclosed.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis maintained the lead from the standing start entering the first corner and began to expand a small lead over Rosenqvist in the opening laps, who could not maintain the leader's pace.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Towards the end of lap one, Holzmann clipped the outside wall out of the final corner, speared across the start/finish straight, and collected Félix da Costa, ending both drivers' chances of a podium finish.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Holzmann retired, but Félix da Costa continued despite minor car damage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet dropped to 17th on the first lap, but returned to 14th by lap seven.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] By the third lap, Bird had moved up to sixth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The mandatory virtual pit stops required all drivers to change cars, began at the end of lap seven, when Bird entered the pit lane.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left a multi-car battle for third with Uusi-Jaakkola, Greco, and Graham Carroll at the conclusion of the next lap in order to make his mandatory pit stop.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left with a clear track ahead of him, and because no other driver was impeding him, he set a series of fast lap times.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] On the tenth lap, Graham Carroll got a run on Uusi-Jaakkola leaving the final corner and steered onto the inside line into the first turn chicane.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Greco made it three abreast on the outside.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] He and Uusi-Jaakkola collided, and the latter touched Graham Carroll's left-rear wheel.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Two of the cars barrel-rolled through the trackside catch fencing and into some palm trees.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The cars glitched quickly and re-rendered themselves onto the circuit.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Both Uusi-Jaakkola and Greco had lost a wheel and dropped several positions.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Virtual racing technology meant the trio emerged unhurt from the crash and the safety car was not used.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] As the eRace progressed, race leader Huis made an error, allowing Rosenqvist to close to within less than two seconds of him.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Rosenqvist made their pit stops together at the end of lap fifteen and emerged in second and third places.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala lapped in the 1 minute, 24 second range, moving him to the front of the field, and requiring Huis and Rosenqvist to focus on battling for second position.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Buemi dropped outside the top ten with four laps remaining when Piquet passed him for tenth.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Ussi-Jaakkola and Bonito battled for fourth, which ended in the latter's favour in the last three laps.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was unchallenged for the rest of the eRace, and was first to cross the start/finish line.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis held off Rosenqvist in the closing laps for second.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Dragon filed a complaint with the race officials following the podium ceremony.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] An examination of data shared by viewers on Twitter shortly after the race revealed that Pahkala had used FanBoost illegally for approximately five laps, rather than the maximum of five seconds due to a software bug.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Hence, Pahkala had 12 seconds added to his race time and was demoted to third.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis inherited the victory with Rosenqvist second.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Bonito finished fourth, ahead of the Finnish duo of Uusi-Jaakkola and Huttu.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] The final classified finishers were López, Bird, Abt, Piquet, Buemi, Elomaa, Frijns, Duval, Greco, Félix da Costa, and Graham Carroll.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis received $200,000 for race victory and Greco got $10,000 for setting the fastest lap.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Huis commented on the victory: "It's very exciting to be here, racing in conjunction with pro drivers during one of the most renowned tech forward events.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Media reaction to the Vegas eRace was mostly positive.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] New England Sports Network's Pat McAssey noted that FE's partnership with ELEAGUE brought sim racing to a mainstream audience and argued that eSports can potentially solve accessibility issues because some people lack the money to purchase a go-kart.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] He argued that FE could help eRacing grow and allow others to use it as an alternative career path to traditional motor racing.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Curtis Moldrich, writing for *Alphr*, echoed similar sentiments, believing that the positive outcome of the Vegas eRace was a testament to FE's forward-thinking philosophy.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Other media outlets received the race more negatively.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] It lacked any sense of real weight or drama, and tied in with the glitches affecting some of the drivers it didn't come anywhere near to producing the excitement of real racing." Jonathan M.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Gitlin of *Ars Technica* felt short-changed watching the eRace and noted the large number of complaints about the quality of the graphics in the Twitch stream.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/2017-vegas-erace] Following the event, some of the competing sim racers were adopted into their respective teams and assisted in the real-life development of their cars through testing and advising, indicating that their opinions were taken seriously, according to FE's eSports manager Matt Huxley.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Since then, the Major circuit has expanded significantly, with recent tournaments advertising a US$1,250,000 prize pool and featuring thirty-two teams from around the world.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Majors are considered to be the most important and prestigious tournaments in the Counter-Strike scene.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The current champions are Team Falcons, who won their first Major at the IEM Cologne Major 2026, the fifth to be held in *Counter-Strike 2*.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Astralis hold the record for the most Major titles with four.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Swedish teams, most notably SK Gaming, dominated early Majors but the Polish roster known as the Golden Five were the most successful lineup.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Many teams from other parts of the world would win Majors, including Team 3D from the United States at CPL Winter 2002 and WCG 2004, NoA from Norway at CPL Winter 2004, mibr from Brazil at ESWC 2006, and WeMade FOX from South Korea at WEM 2010.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On September 16, 2013, a year after the release of *Global Offensive*, Valve announced a US$250,000 community-funded prize pool for the first official CS:GO Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The money was partially community-funded through the game's Arms Deal update, which allowed players to buy in-game skins.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve announced the tournament would take place in Sweden and would be hosted by DreamHack.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The tournament took place in late November and was won by the Swedish team Fnatic who upset Ninjas in Pyjamas in the finals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After Dreamhack 2013, Valve announced they would partner with tournament organizers to host three Majors per year.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] These Majors are the most prestigious events in the competitive CS:GO scene, and the professional players' legacies are often judged by their performances at these tournaments.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The early Majors were dominated by Swedish teams, as Fnatic and NiP combined to win the four of the first six Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] NiP would play in five of the first six grand finals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] When Fnatic won Cologne 2015, they became the first team to win back to back Majors, and the first to win a third Major in total.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] This feat has only been matched by Astralis and Team Vitality, although Vitality did not maintain the same roster core throughout their Major wins.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] At the end of 2015, Valve announced that MLG would host the first Major in North America.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On February 23, 2016, with MLG Columbus 2016 coming up, Valve announced a permanent increase in the prize pool from US$250,000 to US$1,000,000.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] However, Valve reduced the number of Majors per year from three to two.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Luminosity Gaming, a Brazilian team, won the event to becomes the first non-European team to win a Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] This roster would also go on to win back to back Majors, with their second as SK Gaming at ESL One Cologne 2016.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Gambit Esports, made up primarily of players from Kazakhstan, won PGL Major Kraków 2017 to become the first Asian and CIS team to win a Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On December 13, 2017, the general manager of ELEAGUE, the hosts of the ELEAGUE Major: Boston 2018, announced a revised format designed by Valve and ELEAGUE that would expand the number of teams in the Major from sixteen to twenty-four.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] This was also the first Major to take place in multiple cities, as the group stages took place in Atlanta at the Turner Studios.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Cloud9, an American team, won the event to become the first North American team to win a Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After Boston 2018, the Danish team Astralis became the top team in CS:GO and one of the best teams in *Counter-Strike* history.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] With wins at London 2018, Katowice 2019, and Berlin 2019, Astralis become the first team to win three Majors in a row and four majors total.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After Berlin 2019, Valve and ESL announced the following Major, ESL One Rio 2020, which was to be the first Major to be hosted in South America.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Rio 2020, originally scheduled for May, was then postponed to November due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The November Major was announced with a US$2,000,000 prize pool, combining the amounts that would have been set aside for both Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] In September 2020, the Rio Major was officially canceled due to COVID-19.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] In December 2020, Valve moved the 2021 Major from May to October and November, citing concerns over the pandemic.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On January 14, 2021, Valve announced that the championship would be held between October 23 and November 7 in Stockholm.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Over two years after the last Major, PGL Major Stockholm 2021 took place, with favourites Natus Vincere dominating the tournament and becoming the first team in CS:GO history to win a Major without dropping a single map throughout the tournament.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] PGL Major Stockholm 2021 surpassed the long-standing Counter-Strike viewership record 4 times; reaching 2.75 million concurrent viewers in the final.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] FaZe Clan won the PGL Major Antwerp 2022, defeating Natus Vincere 2-0, and becoming the first international team in CS:GO history to win a Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The previously cancelled ESL One Rio 2020 Major was replaced with IEM Rio Major 2022 and was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil on October 31 - November 13, 2022.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Outsiders, a neutral name for esports organization Virtus.pro due to ties with the Russian government in light of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, won the tournament defeating Heroic in the grand final 2-0.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] BLAST Paris Major 2023 was held in Paris on May 8 - May 21, 2023 with a prize pool of $1,250,000 USD.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Shortly after the announcement of Counter-Strike 2, the official CS:GO Twitter account announced that the BLAST Paris Major would be the last CS:GO Major with the next major happening in March 2024 in CS2.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Team Vitality, a French organization with native star player Mathieu 'ZywOo' Herbaut, defeated dark horse GamerLegion by 2–0 to clinch the final CS:GO Major title.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The first *Counter-Strike 2* Major was announced to be the PGL CS2 Major Copenhagen 2024 which was held from March 17–31 in the Royal Arena.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On November 12, 2023, Perfect World, who are responsible for distributing *Counter-Strike 2* in China, announced the second major following the release of *Counter-Strike 2*, taking place in Shanghai between December 1-15, 2024.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Team Spirit defeated FaZe Clan 2-1, with star player donk becoming the youngest player to win a Major and Major MVP at 17 years 324 days old.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] On January 3, 2025, Valve announced a second expansion of the number of teams to thirty-two, starting with the BLAST Austin Major that year.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Team Vitality would win their second Major trophy after defeating The MongolZ 2-1, and their third after defeating FaZe Clan 3-1 at the Budapest Major, in the first Major grand final to be held as a best-of-five.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Starting after Dreamhack 2013, the top eight teams from each Major (those who made it to the playoff stage) earned automatic berths to the next Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The other eight teams, called "Challengers", were decided by regional qualifiers, mainly from Europe and North America.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] A small number of teams have been directly invited or earned attendance from a last chance qualifier to fill final open spots when necessary.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Beginning with the DreamHack Open Cluj-Napoca 2015 qualification cycle, Valve created a single 16-team main qualifier before the Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The bottom eight teams from the previous Major earn automatic berths to the newly formed Major qualifier, and the regional qualifiers now send teams to the main qualifier, instead of directly to the Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] For MLG Columbus 2016 the regional qualifiers, leading into the Major qualifier, were replaced by "Minors".
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Columbus Minor system involved four regional qualifiers and two "last chance" qualifiers, and results in invites going to one team from the Americas, two Asian teams, one CIS team, one European team, and three last chance qualifier spots.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The system was simplified in the following Major, ESL One Cologne 2016, with the removal of the last chance qualifiers.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Four Minors—Asia, CIS, Europe, Americas—were used.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Two teams from each qualifier would go to the Major qualifier, joining the bottom eight teams from the previous Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The top eight teams from the 16-team Major qualifier advance to the Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] At ELEAGUE Major: Boston 2018, the Major qualifier was integrated into the full Major as the first of three phases, expanding the number of teams in each Major to 24.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Major qualifier was renamed the "Challengers Stage", the former group stage was renamed the "Legends Stage", and the playoff stage was named the "Champions Stage".
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] This increased the number of teams getting automatic invites to Majors to 16, while retaining the Minor system to fill the remaining eight spots in phase one of the Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Legends—still made up of the teams who reach the playoff stage—earned an automatic invitation to the Legends Stage of the following Major, while the teams placing 9-16 earned automatic invitations to the Challengers Stage of the following Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] From the PGL Major Stockholm 2021 up until the Perfect World Shanghai Major 2024, no automatic berths were given to any team regardless of their record in the previous Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Despite initially being used for the ESL One Rio Major 2020, the event's cancellation would mean that PGL Major Stockholm 2021 was the first Major that utilized the RMR system.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The very next Major, PGL Major Antwerp 2022, would scrap the points circuit in favor of qualifying tournaments that bore the RMR name, initially and ultimately 2 for Europe (which included the CIS region), 1 for the Americas and 1 for Asia-Pacific.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Teams qualified for their regional RMRs via making the Legends Stage of the previous major or via online qualifying made up of Open Qualifiers, where any team could sign up and compete for RMR spots.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] In addition, regions could gain or lose Challengers and Legends spots in the Major based on the region's results from the previous Major, with 3 Challengers spots reserved for Europe and the Americas and 2 for Asia-Pacific.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] For example, after PGL Major Copenhagen 2024, the Americas region would go from 1 Legends spot and 4 Challengers spot, to 7 Challengers spots for Shanghai, after 4 teams from the Americas qualified for the Elimination Stage, with none making the Playoff stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] For BLAST Austin Major 2025, an extra stage was added to the Major, expanding the number of teams to 32 and stages to four.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Of these, 16 are directly invited from the VRS to the second and third stages.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The other sixteen teams qualified for the Major's first stage via Major Regional Qualifiers, or MRQs, with the next-best teams in each VRS being invited; this system would be scrapped for StarLadder Budapest 2025 as the Stage 1 spots would also be allocated via VRS.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Like with the RMR system, regions can gain and lose invites to the later stages of the Major based on the prior Major's results, but 6 teams each from the Americas and Europe, as well as 4 teams from Asia-Pacific, qualify for the Major in Stage 1.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Unlike traditional sports or other esports leagues, Valve considers the players in each team to have the Major spots, rather than the organization itself.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] For instance, at the ELEAGUE Major 2017, Team EnVyUs placed ninth, meaning it would have an automatic berth at the next Major qualifier.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] However, before the next Major, three of EnVyUs's players transferred to G2 Esports, meaning Team EnVyUs lost its spot at the Major qualifier.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Although the playoff stage of the Majors has generally followed a standard 8-team single-elimination format, the group stages have changed multiple times.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] From 2013 to 2016, Majors used a four group GSL-style format for the group stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] In each four-team group, the two higher seeds would initially face the two lower seeds.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The two winners from the first round of matches would then play to determine which team gets the top seed.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The two losers would also play to eliminate one team.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After this second round of matches, the remaining two teams play to determine which team takes the final playoff spot.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] All group stage games at the first Majors were best-of-ones.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The last Major of 2015 and both Majors in 2016 featured a best-of-three decider in the final match of each group.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The group stage of ESL One Cologne 2015 worked differently.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Initially, the first three matches of the group stage started out the same way as the standard GSL format, determining the group winner.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] However, teams were then reassigned afterwards so that the two losers played from different groups and then the decider match would also be teams from different groups.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Beginning in 2017, the group stage has featured a Swiss-system group stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Before the tournament, teams are divided into four pots, with pot one having the four highest seeds, pot two having the next four highest seeds, and so on.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] A randomly selected team from pot one would face off against a randomly selected team from pot four.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The same process is done with the pots two and three.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After the initial seeded match, teams play five rounds against randomly drawn teams with the same record.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] No two teams play twice unless necessary.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] If a team wins three matches, then that team moves on to the next stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] If a team loses three matches, that team is eliminated.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] All games were best-of-one until the London 2018 Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Boston 2018 Major featured two Swiss group stages; the stage formerly known as the offline Major qualifier was now called the New Challengers stage and the group stage was now rebranded as the New Legends stage.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The London 2018 Major used a slightly different form of the Swiss system, called the Buchholz system, in which matchups were seeded instead of random and the last round featured best-of-three sets.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The next Major, Katowice 2019, featured a crowdsourced Elo system, in which participating teams ranked the 15 other teams before the Legends Stage to create a seeding system for each round of the Swiss system.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Copenhagen 2024 Major changed the names of the two Swiss stages, with the Challengers Stage becoming the Opening Stage and the Legends Stage becoming the Elimination Stage, while the first round match-up seeding for the Swiss stages was tweaked.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] A third Swiss stage was added beginning with the 2025 Austin Major to accompany the expansion to 32 teams.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The Playoffs, known as the New Champions stage and Champions stage beforehand, have featured eight teams at all Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] All matches are best-of-three, single-elimination series.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] When the GSL format was used for group stages, group winners earned top seeds and group runner-ups earned bottom seeds.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Each top seed played a bottom seed in quarterfinals.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] With current Swiss format seeding, the two teams that finish undefeated in the group stage earn the highest seeds.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Two of the three lowest seeds from the group stage (teams that advance with two losses) are randomly selected to play against the high seeds.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Two of the three middle seeds (teams that advance with one loss) are randomly selected to play each other, and the remaining two teams face each other to finalize the bracket.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve would make further changes to the Major format at StarLadder Budapest Major 2025, introducing a best-of-five grand final.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] At the following Major, IEM Cologne Major 2026, the third Swiss-stage group features only best-of-three matches.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve has banned players from attending the Majors for violations of competitive integrity.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] A Valve Anti-Cheat (VAC) ban is the most common way players get banned.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] VAC is an anti-cheat program designed by Valve to detect cheats running in various games, including *Counter-Strike*.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] If cheats are detected, the account is given a permanent lifetime ban from playing on VAC-secured servers.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Other server providers, such as FACEIT and ESEA, have their own anti-cheat systems and work with Valve to detect new cheats.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] One of the most high-profile VAC bans was given to Hovik "KQLY" Tovmassian.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] KQLY, along with several other professional players, was banned while playing for France's best team, Titan.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve has also banned players from Valve-sponsored events for match fixing.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The first Valve ban for match fixing was a response to the iBUYPOWER match fixing scandal, in which esports journalist Richard Lewis revealed that one of North America's best teams, iBUYPOWER, had thrown a match for high-value skins.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve indefinitely banned seven players who were involved in the scandal from attending any Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Tyler "Skadoodle" Latham was the only iBUYPOWER player not to be banned, as he did not receive any payment after the game.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve would later make the bans permanent, causing some controversy in the Counter-Strike community.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Although tournament organizers ESL and DreamHack lifted their own bans on the former iBUYPOWER players in 2017, the Major ban effectively ended the high level careers of two of North America's best in-game leaders (Sam "DaZeD" Marine and Joshua "steel" Nissan) and Braxton "swag" Pierce.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Skadoodle would go on to win a Major with Cloud9.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Following the iBUYPOWER ban, there have been two other match fixing bans, resulting in nine other players being barred from the Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Starting with Cologne 2014, maps were grouped into Active Duty and Reserves, with the former category being used for all Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Stickers are virtual items in the game which players can buy directly using purchasable tokens or indirectly via the Steam marketplace.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] The stickers can then be applied to in-game gun skins.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Valve has released a sticker design for each team attending a Major since Katowice 2014, and a sticker for each professional player's signature since Cologne 2015.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] These two types of stickers come in a variety of styles: paper, glitter, holographic, foil, and gold.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] With each sticker purchase, half of the proceeds go to the player or team and half go to Valve.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Historically, these stickers have been obtainable in game from sticker capsules, with team and player signature stickers separated into Contenders, Challengers and Legends capsules based on team status, but this was changed to the token system starting from the 2026 Cologne Major.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] These sticker capsules are unique for each tournament and can only be purchased at the time of the tournament.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Because of this forced rarity, stickers from early majors tend to become more expensive over time.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After initially costing less than US$10, a "Titan" holographic sticker from Katowice 2014 sold on secondary markets for US$80,000 in 2023, making it the most expensive public sticker trade in the game's history.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Souvenir packages are virtual packages containing a gun skin that are exclusive to CS:GO Majors.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] These "souvenir skins" can rank among the most expensive skins in the game because of their rarity.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After Cloud9 became the first ever North American CS:GO Major champion at Boston 2018, a souvenir skin with the signature of the finals MVP, Tyler "Skadoodle" Latham, sold for US$61,000.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] After certain significant or iconic moments in *Global Offensive* Majors, Valve has added in-game memorials to the location of the event, usually in the form of graffiti or signs.
[src:counter-strike-major-championships/counter-strike-major-championships] Thus far, there have been six moments in Majors that have been memorialized by Valve, though one graffiti was removed when Dust II was updated.
